        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "docs: propose durable agent coordination kernel",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThis is a replacement RFC for the earlier durable-core docs PR (#97467). It keeps the proposal intentionally small and avoids describing implementation as if it already exists on `main`.\n\nThe RFC proposes a durable agent coordination kernel underneath existing OpenClaw surfaces:\n\n- background tasks remain the detached-work ledger;\n- Task Flow remains the multi-step orchestration surface;\n- Workboard remains an optional operator/card surface;\n- sessions remain the model-visible transcript boundary;\n- the proposed kernel only owns coordination identity, event ordering, child links, fan-in readiness, restart recovery markers, and bounded observability.\n\n## Why This Shape\n\nClawSweeper correctly noted that the previous docs stack was hard to review because it documented future code as present behavior and overlapped with Task Flow/product direction. This replacement is proposal-only and asks for maintainer alignment before deeper implementation.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- No Temporal/Restate/Hatchet/LangGraph clone.\n- No default-on behavior change.\n- No raw prompt/task persistence in coordination metadata.\n- No plugin/dashboard/channel coupling.\n- No claim that Task Flow or Workboard should be replaced.\n\n## Review Focus\n\nPlease review whether this is the right architectural boundary for future work:\n\n1. Should this live as a standalone core runtime module, inside Task Flow internals, or as a narrower shared task/session submodule?\n2. Is shared `state/openclaw.sqlite` the right lifecycle home for the first local-first ledger?\n3. Is the proposed primitive set small enough for upstream OpenClaw?\n\n## Tests\n\nDocs-only RFC. No runtime tests were run for this branch.\n",
